      "id": 5,
      "title": "Keeping Your Dog Cool in Hot Weather",
      "type": "Lifestyle",
      "content": "Dogs do not sweat like humans and primarily cool themselves through panting and paw pads. During hot weather, it's essential to provide constant access to fresh, cool water and shaded resting areas to prevent overheating. Avoid strenuous exercise during peak sun hours, typically between 10 a.m. and 4 p.m. You can also use cooling mats, damp towels, or fans to help your dog regulate body temperature. Never leave dogs inside parked cars, as temperatures can rise rapidly, causing heatstroke, which is a life-threatening emergency. Signs of overheating include excessive panting, drooling, weakness, and collapse."
